Rule 1: Cover ≥2 surviving CUIs
The ancestor must be a parent/grandparent of at least 2 of your 100 surviving CUIs. That's what makes it a convergence point — multiple CUIs meet there.
Persistent asthma
  ├── C2887453 (Mild persistent + exacerb)     ← surviving CUI
  ├── C2887456 (Moderate persistent)            ← surviving CUI
  └── C4040110 (Severe exacerb moderate)        ← surviving CUI

Persistent asthma covers 3 surviving CUIs → YES, convergence ✓

Respiratory rate measurement
  └── C0231832 (Respiratory rate)               ← surviving CUI
      (no other surviving CUI under this parent)

Respiratory rate measurement covers 1 surviving CUI → NO, not convergence ✗
→ C0231832 becomes a singleton topic (no grouper found)
If an ancestor covers only 1 CUI, it's not grouping anything. It's just a parent of one concept. No point making it a topic.

Rule 2: IC ≥ floor
The ancestor must be specific enough to be a meaningful clinical label.
Persistent asthma    IC=10.8   ≥ 5.5?  YES → can be a topic ✓
  (means something specific — a clinician recognizes this)

Asthma               IC=7.4    ≥ 5.5?  YES → can be a topic ✓
  (still meaningful)

Disease              IC=1.2    ≥ 5.5?  NO → rejected ✗
  (everything is a disease — useless as a topic label)

Clinical finding     IC=0.5    ≥ 5.5?  NO → rejected ✗
  (even more useless)
Without this rule, "Disease" covers all 100 CUIs. It would become one mega-topic containing everything. The floor prevents that.

Rule 3: Not in the surviving set
The ancestor must be an ancestor, not one of the 100 CUIs itself.
Surviving set: {C2887453, C2887456, C4040110, ...}

Persistent asthma (C0581122) — is it in the surviving set? NO → can be grouper ✓

C2887456 (Moderate persistent) — is it in the surviving set? YES → can't be grouper ✗
Why? If a surviving CUI becomes its own topic, you get a topic with one member — itself. That's not grouping. It's a CUI pointing at itself. The grouper must be an ancestor that sits above the surviving CUIs in the hierarchy, not one of them.

All three together:
BFS found ancestor X.

  Does X cover ≥2 survivors?     → is it worth grouping?
  Is X's IC ≥ floor?             → is it specific enough?
  Is X outside the surviving set? → is it actually an ancestor?

  All YES → X becomes a topic grouping key
  Any NO  → X is skippedpull alll these topic formation in one cell to copy12:23 PMConsolidated topic formation explanations for convenient copyingConsolidated topic formation explanations for convenient copyingStage 6: HierarchicalTopicBuilder
Input: only CUI codes. No phrases, no text. The builder doesn't know which phrase produced which CUI.
How it works: BFS walks UP the UMLS hierarchy from each surviving CUI. Where multiple CUIs converge to a shared ancestor, that ancestor becomes a grouping key.

Parameters
ParameterValueTypeWhy this valuemax_depth5FIXEDSafety cap. IC gradient does the real stopping. 5 is never the binding constraint._HTB_IC_GRADIENT_RATIO0.3FIXEDAt hop 3+, stop if IC(parent) < 30% of IC(current). Catches the "IC cliff". Hops 1-2 always followed (grace period)._HTB_IC_FLOOR_PERCENTILE10FIXEDIC floor = p10 (10th percentile) of surviving CUI ICs. The percentile number (10) is fixed. The floor VALUE it produces changes per run.max_coveragemax(2, n/√n)ADAPTIVEFrom IDF literature. Ancestor covering more than this is too broad. Small set (n=5): max=2. Large (n=100): max=10.Convergence rule≥2 CUIs, not in surviving setFIXED≥2 ensures actual grouping. "Not in surviving set" prevents a CUI from being its own topic.Subtopic selectionhighest IC first, greedyFIXEDMost specific convergence points become subtopics. Each CUI belongs to one subtopic only.

How the walk works
BFS walks UP from every surviving CUI. Three things can stop it:
Hop 1: ALWAYS walk                           (grace period)
Hop 2: ALWAYS walk                           (grace period)
Hop 3: walk IF IC ratio ≥ 0.3               (gradient check starts)
Hop 4: walk IF IC ratio ≥ 0.3
Hop 5: walk IF IC ratio ≥ 0.3, then STOP    (max depth, hard cap)
Example — walking UP from "Severe persistent asthma" (IC=13.8):
Hop 1: Persistent asthma       IC=10.8   grace → walk
                                          ratio not checked yet
Hop 2: Asthma                  IC=7.4    grace → walk
                                          ratio not checked yet
Hop 3: Respiratory disorder    IC=3.2    ratio = 3.2/7.4 = 0.43 > 0.3 → walk
Hop 4: Disease                 IC=1.2    ratio = 1.2/3.2 = 0.38 > 0.3 → walk
Hop 5: Clinical finding        IC=0.5    MAX DEPTH → stop
Sparse branch with cliff:
Hop 1: Some specific procedure IC=12.0   grace → walk
Hop 2: Procedure category      IC=8.0    grace → walk
Hop 3: Procedure               IC=0.8    ratio = 0.8/8.0 = 0.10 < 0.3 → STOP
→ stopped at hop 3 by gradient

IC gradient ratio (0.3) — why?
At hop 3+, check: is parent's IC at least 30% of current node's IC?
Asthma (IC=7.4) → Respiratory disorder (IC=3.2)
  ratio = 3.2/7.4 = 0.43 > 0.3 → keep walking (gradual decline, still useful)

Disease (IC=1.2) → Clinical finding (IC=0.1)
  ratio = 0.1/1.2 = 0.08 < 0.3 → STOP (cliff — jumped from meaningful to useless)
0.3 means: allow a 70% drop per hop. Generous enough for gradual IC decrease. Strict enough to catch sudden cliffs. Tested: 0.2 goes too deep, 0.5 stops too early.
Hops 1-2 are grace period because some branches have a legitimate big IC jump at hop 1 (very specific leaf under a broad parent). You don't want to cut off the first two levels.

IC floor — what it is
Not constant. Computed per run.
_HTB_IC_FLOOR_PERCENTILE = 10  ← this is fixed (always 10th percentile)

But the result depends on your data:
  Query (5 CUIs, all IC ~14.8):     p10 → floor ≈ 14.8
  Document (138 CUIs, IC 3-15):     p10 → floor ≈ 10.5
  Another doc (200 CUIs, IC 5-15):  p10 → floor ≈ 6.2
p10 = the value at position 10% in the sorted IC list. One number. Not an average of the bottom 10%.
100 CUIs sorted by IC:
  position 1:   IC=3.2
  position 2:   IC=4.1
  ...
  position 10:  IC=5.5   ← THIS is p10. One number.
  ...
  position 100: IC=14.8

floor = 5.5
Why p10: 90% of your CUIs are above this floor. Only the truly broad bottom 10% set the boundary. Low enough to find valid groupers. High enough to block root-adjacent concepts.

IC floor — how it's used
BFS walks UP from ALL CUIs (not just the bottom 10%). Every ancestor found is checked against the floor. Only ancestors ABOVE the floor can become topic grouping keys.
BFS found ancestor "Persistent asthma" (IC=10.8):
  above floor (10.5)?  YES → eligible as grouping key

BFS found ancestor "Asthma" (IC=7.4):
  above floor (10.5)?  NO → rejected, too broad

BFS found ancestor "Disease" (IC=1.2):
  above floor (10.5)?  NO → rejected, way too broad
Without the floor, "Asthma" (IC=7.4) becomes a grouping key. It would pull in severity variants, medications, procedures — everything asthma-related into one mega-topic. Clinically useless.

Three rules for a grouping key
BFS collects ancestors. Not every ancestor becomes a topic. Three rules filter:
Rule 1: Cover ≥2 surviving CUIs (convergence)
The ancestor must be parent/grandparent of at least 2 of your surviving CUIs. That's what makes it a convergence point — multiple CUIs meet there.
Persistent asthma
  ├── C2887453 (Mild persistent + exacerb)     ← surviving CUI
  ├── C2887456 (Moderate persistent)            ← surviving CUI
  └── C4040110 (Severe exacerb moderate)        ← surviving CUI

Covers 3 → YES ✓ (worth grouping)

Respiratory rate measurement
  └── C0231832 (Respiratory rate)               ← surviving CUI
      (no other surviving CUI under this)

Covers 1 → NO ✗ (not grouping anything, C0231832 becomes a singleton topic)
Rule 2: IC ≥ floor (specific enough)
The ancestor must be specific enough to be a meaningful clinical label.
Persistent asthma    IC=10.8   ≥ 10.5?  YES → meaningful label ✓
Asthma               IC=7.4    ≥ 10.5?  NO  → too broad ✗
Disease              IC=1.2    ≥ 10.5?  NO  → everything is a disease ✗
Rule 3: Not in the surviving set (must be an ancestor)
The grouping key must sit ABOVE the surviving CUIs, not be one of them.
Persistent asthma (C0581122) — in surviving set? NO → can be grouper ✓
C2887456 (Moderate persistent) — in surviving set? YES → can't be grouper ✗
If a surviving CUI becomes its own topic, you get a topic with one member — itself. The grouper must be an ancestor that sits above.
All three together:
BFS found ancestor X.
  Does X cover ≥2 survivors?       → is it worth grouping?
  Is X's IC ≥ floor?               → is it specific enough?
  Is X outside the surviving set?  → is it actually an ancestor?
  All YES → X becomes a topic grouping key
  Any NO  → X is skipped

max_coverage — preventing mega-groupers
Even if an ancestor passes all three rules, it might cover too many CUIs. max_coverage = max(2, n/√n) limits this.
n=100: max_coverage = max(2, 100/√100) = max(2, 10) = 10
n=25:  max_coverage = max(2, 25/√25) = max(2, 5) = 5
n=5:   max_coverage = max(2, 5/√5) = max(2, 2.2) = 2
An ancestor covering more than max_coverage CUIs is rejected even if it passes the three rules. From IDF literature: √n is the threshold for "too common." An ancestor covering that many concepts provides no discrimination.

Convergence point selection
Multiple ancestors can pass all rules. Sort by IC (highest first). Assign greedily.
138 CUIs, floor=10.5

Convergence points found (sorted by IC):
  Exacerbation of asthma (IC=12.9) → covers C1960050, C2887453, C4041140 → Subtopic A
  Moderate persistent asthma (IC=12.3) → covers C2887456, C4040110 → Subtopic B
  Mild persistent asthma (IC=12.1) → covers C4040055, C4040085 → Subtopic C
  Persistent asthma (IC=10.8) → covers all 7 → TOPIC GROUPER (ancestor of all 3 subtopics)

Greedy: highest IC first gets first pick of unassigned CUIs.
  Exacerbation (12.9) claims C1960050, C2887453, C4041140
  Moderate (12.3) claims C2887456, C4040110
  Mild (12.1) claims C4040055, C4040085
  Persistent asthma (10.8) covers all 3 subtopics → becomes the topic grouper

Worked example — query: 5 CUIs → 1 topic
IC floor = p10([14.8, 14.8, 14.8, 14.8, 14.8]) ≈ 14.8
max_coverage = max(2, 5/√5) = 2

UMLS hierarchy tree (BFS UP from 5 surviving CUIs):

✘ Procedure                                    IC=0.8   excluded (below floor)
│
✘ Surgical procedure on joint                  IC=3.1   excluded
│
✘ Operation on knee                            IC=6.4   excluded
│
